By the way, it’s not wrong at all to call

00:13:27.829 --> 00:13:31.249
a boat simply “it”, and indeed the Lloyds

00:13:31.259 --> 00:13:33.559
Register of Shipping, which knows a thing

00:13:33.559 --> 00:13:36.139
or two about boats, calls a ship “it”.

00:13:37.479 --> 00:13:39.809
And it’s not just ships that

00:13:39.959 --> 00:13:41.539
get given genders in English.

00:13:41.999 --> 00:13:45.259
Cars and machines are often feminine

00:13:45.399 --> 00:13:47.489
in English, but typically only when

00:13:47.489 --> 00:13:49.649
the person talking about them has some

00:13:49.649 --> 00:13:51.619
kind of close relationship with them.

00:13:52.759 --> 00:13:55.419
All that being said, this is a pretty

00:13:55.569 --> 00:13:58.949
niche, unusual, way of speaking, so for

00:13:58.959 --> 00:14:01.229
all intents and purposes, it is safe

00:14:01.229 --> 00:14:03.609
to assume that there are no genders

00:14:03.729 --> 00:14:05.879
used to describe objects in English.

00:14:07.089 --> 00:14:09.279
There are, of course, still gendered

00:14:09.279 --> 00:14:11.739
terms used to describe people.

00:14:12.409 --> 00:14:14.539
Now, this is perhaps controversial

00:14:14.539 --> 00:14:16.319
territory we’re getting into here,

00:14:16.629 --> 00:14:19.229
but the English language historically

00:14:19.459 --> 00:14:22.439
has male and female pronouns that are

00:14:22.439 --> 00:14:25.809
used to describe people - he/him, and

00:14:25.999 --> 00:14:29.109
she/her, with the third person plural,

00:14:29.449 --> 00:14:32.399
they, being used when the gender of

00:14:32.399 --> 00:14:35.279
a person is unspecified or unknown.

00:14:36.469 --> 00:14:39.459
And in English, nouns describing

00:14:39.459 --> 00:14:41.109
the job someone does have

00:14:41.109 --> 00:14:43.199
historically been slightly different

00:14:43.339 --> 00:14:45.739
depending on that person's gender.

00:14:46.399 --> 00:14:48.359
Headmaster or Headmistress.

00:14:48.739 --> 00:14:50.509
Policeman or Policewoman.

00:14:51.009 --> 00:14:52.739
Actor or Actress.

00:14:53.009 --> 00:14:54.479
Waiter or Waitress.

00:14:55.429 --> 00:14:58.659
In most cases, the male variant

00:14:58.679 --> 00:15:00.849
is the dominant one, and the

00:15:01.049 --> 00:15:03.549
female version is an alternative.

00:15:04.719 --> 00:15:06.649
Clearly, this is problematic.

00:15:07.289 --> 00:15:09.816
If a young girl only hears about

00:15:10.086 --> 00:15:13.565
policemen, or firemen, or postmen

00:15:14.010 --> 00:15:16.836
or businessmen, or even if a young

00:15:16.856 --> 00:15:19.396
boy hears these terms as standard,

00:15:19.720 --> 00:15:21.666
it suggests that these are things

00:15:21.666 --> 00:15:23.556
that can only be done by men.

00:15:24.616 --> 00:15:26.946
Over the past few decades, there has

00:15:26.946 --> 00:15:29.176
been a move to try to standardise

00:15:29.196 --> 00:15:31.096
these terms in English, to try

00:15:31.116 --> 00:15:33.626
to create more inclusive language

00:15:34.856 --> 00:15:37.786
In some cases, the male variant is

00:15:37.786 --> 00:15:39.996
chosen as the standard, so there

00:15:39.996 --> 00:15:42.566
are, for example, no longer actors

00:15:42.586 --> 00:15:45.126
and actresses, simply “actors”.

00:15:46.286 --> 00:15:49.926
In other cases, a new, non-gendered term

00:15:49.926 --> 00:15:52.796
is chosen, so there aren’t Policemen and

00:15:52.806 --> 00:15:55.784
Policewomen, but rather police officers.

00:15:56.667 --> 00:15:57.746
All good so far.

00:15:58.726 --> 00:16:01.976
Perhaps even more strangely, in American

00:16:01.976 --> 00:16:04.536
English a decision has been taken to

00:16:04.756 --> 00:16:07.366
change the Spanish language, when used

00:16:07.366 --> 00:16:09.716
in English, so someone is no longer

00:16:09.906 --> 00:16:13.192
Latino or Latina, they are Latinx.

00:16:14.116 --> 00:16:16.356
The idea of creating an inclusive

00:16:16.356 --> 00:16:18.817
term does, it appears, come

00:16:18.817 --> 00:16:20.746
from a place of good intentions.

00:16:21.456 --> 00:16:23.276
But this particular example of

00:16:23.576 --> 00:16:26.826
“Latinx” has largely been ridiculed

00:16:26.836 --> 00:16:28.536
by the Hispanic population.

00:16:29.256 --> 00:16:33.106
Only 2-3% of Hispanic people reportedly

00:16:33.166 --> 00:16:35.416
use the term to describe themselves,

00:16:35.836 --> 00:16:38.076
and it has been criticised as an

00:16:38.076 --> 00:16:41.126
example of linguistic imperialism, of

00:16:41.296 --> 00:16:44.066
non-Spanish-speaking Americans changing

00:16:44.096 --> 00:16:46.886
Spanish to solve a non-existent problem.

00:16:47.896 --> 00:16:50.366
And as to the question of what is

00:16:50.366 --> 00:16:52.496
the effect of a language having

00:16:52.506 --> 00:16:55.036
grammatical gender or not, and what

00:16:55.066 --> 00:16:57.026
is the effect of English having

00:16:57.026 --> 00:16:59.306
gendered pronouns but not grammatical

00:16:59.306 --> 00:17:02.036
gender, well this is a tricky one.

00:17:03.156 --> 00:17:06.456
There was a prominent study from 2011 that

00:17:06.456 --> 00:17:09.816
looked at gender equality in 111 different

00:17:09.816 --> 00:17:12.536
countries and found that countries where

00:17:12.536 --> 00:17:15.176
gendered languages were spoken tended

00:17:15.196 --> 00:17:17.626
to have lower levels of gender equality.

00:17:18.346 --> 00:17:20.346
So, if you live in a country that

00:17:20.506 --> 00:17:23.706
assigns genders to objects, you are more

00:17:23.706 --> 00:17:26.056
likely to experience gender inequality.

00:17:27.226 --> 00:17:30.136
You might think, well, if that’s the case,

00:17:30.176 --> 00:17:33.076
then presumably countries with no gender

00:17:33.246 --> 00:17:35.816
in their language would be beacons of

00:17:35.816 --> 00:17:38.476
gender equality, would be great places in

00:17:38.476 --> 00:17:41.546
terms of equality between men and women.

00:17:42.916 --> 00:17:44.966
Some, Finland, for example,

00:17:45.266 --> 00:17:47.166
score very highly on this count.

00:17:47.956 --> 00:17:50.706
Finnish is a language without any genders,

00:17:50.866 --> 00:17:53.076
neither grammatical nor in personal

00:17:53.076 --> 00:17:55.646
pronouns, and Finland is a country

00:17:55.646 --> 00:17:58.156
with high levels of gender equality.

00:17:59.356 --> 00:18:01.996
Others, Cameroon, China and

00:18:01.996 --> 00:18:04.036
Turkey, for example, do not.

00:18:04.906 --> 00:18:07.256
These countries don’t use gendered

00:18:07.256 --> 00:18:09.606
language, but they don’t score very

00:18:09.606 --> 00:18:11.516
well in terms of gender equality.

00:18:12.586 --> 00:18:14.886
Interestingly, countries where Natural

00:18:14.896 --> 00:18:16.526
Gender languages like English are

00:18:16.526 --> 00:18:19.186
spoken, where pronouns have gender

00:18:19.216 --> 00:18:22.246
but objects do not, score highest

00:18:22.526 --> 00:18:24.786
overall, they are generally the best

00:18:24.786 --> 00:18:26.896
places in terms of gender equality.

00:18:27.996 --> 00:18:30.346
Clearly, the language spoken in the

00:18:30.346 --> 00:18:33.296
country is only one factor here, but

00:18:33.406 --> 00:18:35.326
it is certainly an interesting piece

00:18:35.326 --> 00:18:38.196
of research, and shows that even if

00:18:38.226 --> 00:18:40.906
your language has no inbuilt gender

00:18:40.956 --> 00:18:43.396
inequality, it certainly doesn’t mean that

00:18:43.396 --> 00:18:45.296
this will be the case for your society.

00:18:46.886 --> 00:18:48.546
So, what does this all

00:18:48.556 --> 00:18:50.226
mean for English learners?

00:18:50.766 --> 00:18:52.346
Well, not a lot, really..

00:18:52.996 --> 00:18:54.636
The good news for you is that

00:18:54.636 --> 00:18:56.726
grammatical gender is one less

00:18:56.726 --> 00:18:58.146
thing you need to worry about.

00:18:58.966 --> 00:19:01.926
When you talk about a turnip, call it it.

00:19:02.466 --> 00:19:03.206
When you talk about a

00:19:03.206 --> 00:19:05.596
chair, call it “it” too.

00:19:06.326 --> 00:19:07.676
And when you’re talking about

00:19:07.676 --> 00:19:10.286
a boat, well the truth is that

00:19:10.286 --> 00:19:12.486
you can call it “it” as well.

00:19:14.518 --> 00:19:17.098
Ok then, that is it for today’s

00:19:17.118 --> 00:19:20.158
episode on gender in language, and

00:19:20.218 --> 00:19:22.488
in particular, gender in English.

00:19:22.858 --> 00:19:24.718
I hope it was an interesting one, and

00:19:24.968 --> 00:19:26.308
that it might have left you thinking

00:19:26.328 --> 00:19:28.098
a bit about your native language.

00:19:28.818 --> 00:19:30.698
Did you grow up speaking a grammatically

00:19:30.698 --> 00:19:33.778
gendered language like French or Spanish,

00:19:34.018 --> 00:19:36.648
a non-gendered language like Turkish

00:19:36.648 --> 00:19:39.518
or Mandarin, or a naturally gendered

00:19:39.518 --> 00:19:42.438
language like English, Danish or Swedish?

00:19:42.948 --> 00:19:45.038
How do you think this affected you,

00:19:45.218 --> 00:19:47.398
and the society you grew up in?

00:19:47.998 --> 00:19:49.938
I would love to know, so let’s

00:19:49.938 --> 00:19:51.268
